entially a neat feature for programming defensively, so guard to me is stronger fit thematically in that sense.<br></p><p>&gt; On 19 Feb 2016, at 21:49, John Flanagan via swift-evolution &lt;swift-evolution at swift.org&gt; wrote:<br>&gt; <br>&gt; The functionality of ‘guard’ is great and this proposal has nothing to do with changing that. The only suggestion is that the word ‘ensure’ would better communicate what a ‘guard’ statement does to those encountering it for the first time and would make code more readable in general.<br>&gt; <br>&gt; Example:<br>&gt; <br>&gt; ensure foo != nil else {<br>&gt;    return;<br>&gt; }<br>&gt; <br>&gt; -John<br>&gt; _______________________________________________<br>&gt; swift-evolution mailing list<br>&gt; swift-evolution at swift.org<br>&gt; https://lists.swift.org/mailman/listinfo/swift-evolution<br></p><p>-------------- next part --------------<br>An HTML attachment was scrubbed...<br>URL: &lt;https://lists.swift.org/pipermail/swift-evolution/attachments/20160223/f3974259/attachment.html&gt;<br></p></div></li></ul></li></ul></div>    </main>
